Absolute speedup

Absolute speed-up

Usually n \small n n ﻿ is kept fixed and p \small p p ﻿ gets varied.

  • Upper boundary of processors

    Implicitly there is an upper boundary of processors for which it does not make sense to add additional processors.

    1. S p ( n ) = c 1 ⋅ p \color{pink}\small S_p(n) = c_1\cdot p S p ​ ( n ) = c 1 ​ ⋅ p ﻿

      for some c 1 < 1 \small c_1 <1 c 1 ​ < 1 ﻿

    1. S p ( n ) = c 2 ⋅ p \color{pink}\small S_p(n) = c_2\cdot \sqrt p S p ​ ( n ) = c 2 ​ ⋅ p ​ ﻿

      for some c 2 < 1 \small c_2 <1 c 2 ​ < 1 ﻿

Limit of absolute speedup

Linear speedup S p ( n ) ∈ O ( p ) \small S_p(n) \in O(p) S p ​ ( n ) ∈ O ( p ) ﻿ can not be exceeded.

Tseq ( n ) ≤ p ⋅ Tpar ( p , n ) \color{pink}\small \small \text{Tseq}(n) \leq p \cdot \text{Tpar}(p,n) Tseq ( n ) ≤ p ⋅ Tpar ( p , n ) ﻿

Perfect speed-up is rare and hardly achievable.

Sometimes we experimentally get super-linear speedup but its because of randomization, non determinism or because algorithms are not comparable (also possible by using caches on multiple processors).

Work-optimal parallel algorithm

Wpar ( n ) ∈ O ( Wseq ( n ) ) = O ( Tseq ( n ) ) \color{pink}\small \text{Wpar}(n) \in O(\text{Wseq}(n)) = O(\text{Tseq}(n)) Wpar ( n ) ∈ O ( Wseq ( n )) = O ( Tseq ( n )) ﻿

has potential for linear speedup.

  • Proof

    Lets say there is a work-optimal algorithm with:

    Tpar ( p , n ) = max ⁡ 0 ≤ i < p T i ( n ) \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) = \max_{0\leq i<p} T_i(n) Tpar ( p , n ) = max 0 ≤ i < p ​ T i ​ ( n ) ﻿

    ∑ 0 ≤ i < p T i ( n ) = Tseq ( n ) \small \sum_{0\leq i <p} T_i(n) = \text{Tseq}(n) ∑ 0 ≤ i < p ​ T i ​ ( n ) = Tseq ( n ) ﻿

    We schedule Par \small \text{Par} Par ﻿ on a smaller number of processors p ′ \small p' p ′ ﻿ in such a way that no processor has any “idle time” (pretty difficult to do this in practice) .

    Then:

    ∑ 0 ≤ i < p ′ T i ( n ) = p ′ ⋅ Tpar ( p ′ , n ) ∈ O ( Tseq ( n ) ) \small \sum_{0\leq i <p'}T_i(n) = p' \cdot \text{Tpar}(p',n)\in O(\text{Tseq}(n)) ∑ 0 ≤ i < p ′ ​ T i ​ ( n ) = p ′ ⋅ Tpar ( p ′ , n ) ∈ O ( Tseq ( n )) ﻿

    This way the algorithm is cost-optimal and therefore has linear speedup.

Relative speedup

Overhead

Parallelization Overhead

= Work that does not have to be done by a sequential algorithm like cooridination (communication, synchronization) and redundant computation.

When there is no overhead we can parallelize perfectly: Tpar ( p , n ) = Tseq ( n ) / p \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) = \text{Tseq}(n)/p Tpar ( p , n ) = Tseq ( n ) / p ﻿

Each Processor has Task T i ( n ) \small T_i(n) T i ​ ( n ) ﻿ and Overhead O i ( n ) \small O_i(n) O i ​ ( n ) ﻿ in its work:

Wpar ( p , n ) = ∑ 0 ≤ i < p T i ( n ) + O i ( n ) \small \text{Wpar}(p,n) = \sum_{0\leq i <p} T_i(n) + O_i(n) Wpar ( p , n ) = ∑ 0 ≤ i < p ​ T i ​ ( n ) + O i ​ ( n ) ﻿

Therefore

Tpar ( 1 , n ) ≥ Tseq ( n ) \color{pink}\small \text{Tpar}(1,n) \geq \text{Tseq}(n) Tpar ( 1 , n ) ≥ Tseq ( n ) ﻿

Load Balancing

Load imbalance

Differece betweeen max and min work+overhead.

∣ max ⁡ ( T i ( n ) + O i ( n ) )    −    min ⁡ ( T i ( n ) + O i ( n ) ) ∣ \color{pink}\small |\max (T_i(n) + O_i(n)) ~~-~~ \min (T_i(n) + O_i(n)) | ∣ m a x ( T i ​ ( n ) + O i ​ ( n ))     −     m i n ( T i ​ ( n ) + O i ​ ( n )) ∣ ﻿

Load balancing

Achieving an even amount of work for all processors i , j \small i,j i , j ﻿ :

Tpar ( i , n ) ≈ Tpar ( j , n ) \color{pink}\small \text{Tpar}(i,n) \approx \text{Tpar}(j,n) Tpar ( i , n ) ≈ Tpar ( j , n ) ﻿

Static, oblivious

Splitting problem in p \small p p ﻿ pieces, regardless of the input (except it’s size) .

Static, problem dependent, adaptive

Splitting problem in p \small p p ﻿ pieces, using the structure of the input.

Dynamic

Dynamically (during program execution) readjusting the work assigned to processors.

This means some overhead.

Max speedup gets very limited and the constant fraction becomes a “sequential overhead”.

Amdahl’s Law (parallel version): Sequential bottleneck / overhead

Let program of Seq \small \text{Seq} Seq ﻿ contain two fractions, independent of n \small n n ﻿ :

  • “perfectly parallelizable” fraction r \color{pink}\small r r ﻿
  • “purely sequential” fraction s = ( 1 − r ) \color{pink}\small s=(1-r) s = ( 1 − r ) ﻿ (can’t be parallelized at all)

The maximum achievable speedup (independent of n \small n n ﻿ ) :

S p ( n ) = 1 / s \color{pink}\small S_p(n) = 1/s S p ​ ( n ) = 1/ s ﻿

  • Proof

    Tseq ( n ) = ( s + r ) ⋅ Tseq ( n ) \small \text{Tseq}(n) = (s+r)\cdot \text{Tseq}(n) Tseq ( n ) = ( s + r ) ⋅ Tseq ( n ) ﻿

    Tpar ( p , n ) = s ⋅ Tseq ( n ) + r p ⋅ Tseq ( n ) \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) = s \cdot \text{Tseq}(n) + \large \frac{r}{p} \small \cdot \text{Tseq}(n) Tpar ( p , n ) = s ⋅ Tseq ( n ) + p r ​ ⋅ Tseq ( n ) ﻿

    S p ( n ) = 1 / ( s + r / p ) \color{pink}\small S_p(n) = 1/(s+r/p) S p ​ ( n ) = 1/ ( s + r / p ) ﻿

We want to avoid Amdahl’s law at all cost.

I/O, initialization of global data structures, shared data structures, everything that takes O ( n ) \small O(n) O ( n ) ﻿ time and work

Scalability

If an algorithm does not have constant efficiency and it’s speedup dependens on n \small n n ﻿

we can aim to maintain some constant efficiency e \small e e ﻿ through

increasing the problem size n \small n n ﻿ with the number of processors p \small p p ﻿

using the iso-efficiency function.

Weak scalability

Parallel algorithm scales weakly relative to sequential algorithm

if there is a slowly growing iso-function f \small f f ﻿ such that:

n ∈ Ω ( f ( p ) )    ⟹    E p ( n ) = e \color{pink}\small n \in \Omega(f(p)) \implies E_p(n) = e n ∈ Ω ( f ( p )) ⟹ E p ​ ( n ) = e ﻿

The growth of f \small f f ﻿ is given by the input-size-scaling-function g \small g g ﻿ .

  • Average work per processor must be constant by increasing n \small n n ﻿ .

    w = Tseq ( n ) / p \small w = \text{Tseq}(n)/p w = Tseq ( n ) / p ﻿

  • Tpar ( p , n ) \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) Tpar ( p , n ) ﻿ must be constant

g ( p ) = 1 / Tseq ( p ⋅ w ) \color{pink} \small g(p) = 1/\text{Tseq}(p\cdot w) g ( p ) = 1/ Tseq ( p ⋅ w ) ﻿

f ( p ) ∈ O ( g ( p ) ) \color{pink}\small f(p) \in O(g(p)) f ( p ) ∈ O ( g ( p )) ﻿

Exception to this rule:

If sequential time > linear then constant efficiency requires n \small n n ﻿ to grow faster than said here.

In that case constant work is maintained with decreasing efficiency.

Strong scalability

Algorithm is strongly scalable if f ( p ) = O ( 1 ) \small f(p) = O(1) f ( p ) = O ( 1 ) ﻿ .

This is almost never the case: all algorithms are at best weakly scalable.

At least as much work is required as there are processors.

But often, constants and lower order terms can safely be ignored - then that the algorithm is strongly scalable for some range of n \small n n ﻿ and p \small p p ﻿ .

Scalability Analysis

https://hpc.llnl.gov/documentation/tutorials/introduction-parallel-computing-tutorial##LimitsCosts

How well does parallel algorithm perform empirically against sequential counterpart as we scale up to the solution?

Scalability analysis is theoretical and practical.

Empirical speedup

= absolute speedup

Assumes that Tseq ( n ) \small \text{Tseq}(n) Tseq ( n ) ﻿ can be measured.

Not the case for very large n , p \small n,p n , p ﻿ .

Weak scaling analysis

Goal: running larger problem in same amount of time.

  • p \small p p ﻿ is increased
  • n \small n n ﻿ is increased
  • Average work per processor stays fixed

The total problem size n \small n n ﻿ is proportional to the number of processors used.

Weakly scalable if Tpar ( p , n ) \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) Tpar ( p , n ) ﻿ remains constant for non scaled input.

Strong scaling analysis

Goal: running same problem size faster.

  • n \small n n ﻿ is kept fixed
  • p \small p p ﻿ is increased

Strongly scalable up to Prallelism \small \text{Prallelism} Prallelism ﻿ -cores if Tpar ( p , n ) \small \text{Tpar}(p,n) Tpar ( p , n ) ﻿ decreases proportionally to p \small p p ﻿ .
